04572nmm a2200553Ia 9780814796146DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147961467 a10.18574/nyu/9780814796146.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681041  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0540002bisacsh1 aMcGinley, Ann C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMasculinity at Work :bEmployment Discrimination through a Different Lens /cAnn C. McGinley. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Bullying Masculinities -- tPart I Masculinities Theory and Title VII -- t1 Masculinities’ Relationship to Title VII -- tPart II Focusing on Gender-and Sex-Based Harassment -- t2 Background to Gender-and Sex-Based Harassment Law -- t3 Evaluating Harassment Occurring “Because of Sex” -- t4 A Question of Standards: Reasonable Men? -- tPart III Sharpening Disparate Treatment and Disparate Impact Claims -- t5 The Law of Disparate Treatment and Impact -- t6 Intent in Disparate Treatment Litigation -- t7 Establishing Disparate Treatment through Masculinities -- t8 Proving Disparate Impact through Masculinities -- tPart IV Practical Considerations: Experts and Evidentiary Constructs -- t9 Educating Judges and Juries about Masculinities -- tConclusion: The Future of Masculinities -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn late October 2013, the Miami Dolphins’ player Jonathan Martin walked out on his team and checked into a mental health institution. The original story implied that Martin could not take the professional pressure. Within days, the story changed. News sources reported that Martin’s teammates had repeatedly bullied him and as a result, the twenty-four year-old African American player suffered serious depression. The response was skeptical, and many opined the harassment involved was simply locker room banter that all players endure; essentially, that boys will be boys.Masculinity at Work uses the Jonathan Martin case and others to analyze Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 through the lens of masculinities theory. Illustrating how harassment and discrimination can occur because of sex even if the gendered nature of the behavior remains unseen to onlookers, this book educates readers about the invisibility of masculine structures and practices, how society constructs concepts of masculinity, and how men (and sometimes women) perform masculinity in different ways depending on their identities and situational contexts. Using a sophisticated mix of legal, gender, and social science analysis, the author demonstrates how masculinities theory can also offer significant insights into the behaviors and motivations of employers, as well as workplace structures that disadvantage both men and women who do not conform to gender stereotypes. Both a theoretical disposition and a practical guide for legal counsel and judges on the interpretation of sex and race discrimination cases, Masculinity at Work explains how this theory can be used to interpret Title VII in new, liberating ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Labor & Employment.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814796146.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814796146423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814796146/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STM